By Temitope Adebayo India’s top carmaker Maruti Suzuki has concluded plans to recall 17,362 vehicles manufactured between Dec. 8, 2022 and Jan. 12, 2023 over a possible defect in its airbag controllers. The recall, which the company announced on Wednesday, is to inspect and replace the affected part of the airbag controller, which could, in rare situations, not deploy the airbags and seat belt pretensioners in the event of a vehicle crash, Maruti added. READ ALSO: President Muhammadu Buhari to visit Lagos The affected models are Alto K10, S-Presso, Eeco, Brezza, Baleno and Grand Vitara, the company said in a regulatory filing. By Temitope Adebayo Suzuki by CFAO has proven its willingness to contribute its quota towards the empowerment of women with the Suzuki Empower Her (SEH) program. The training programme, which lasted four months, ended with a graduation ceremony recently, for the first set of female automotive technicians in its maiden… In "Business" A heavily armed group, which identified itself as ‘Angry Vipers’ has threatened to attack Anambra-born businessman, Obi Cubana. They issued the threat in a viral video on Thursday in which it also gave the Southeast Governors 21 days ultimatum to ensure the release of Nnamdi Kanu, leader of the Indigenous… In "News" Rishi Sunak has emerged the new Prime Minister of the United Kingdom. Recall that Liz Truss, former Prime minister, had resigned, saying she could no longer deliver the mandate on which she was elected by the conservative Party. According to an announcement made by Sir Graham Brady, only one nomination… In "Headlines"